## **Chapter 2: Express.js Deep Dive**

Express.js is a minimalist and flexible web framework for Node.js, designed to simplify the process of building robust APIs and web applications. Unlike raw Node.js, which requires manual handling of HTTP requests and responses, Express provides a structured way to manage routes, middleware, and server configurations. In this chapter, we’ll dive deep into Express.js, covering installation, middleware, routing, and building a simple API endpoint.

---

## **Installing and Configuring Express.js**

Before diving into Express, ensure you have **Node.js** installed (version 14 or later recommended). You can verify this by running:

```bash
node -v
npm -v
```

### **Step 1: Initialize a Node.js Project**
Create a new directory for your project and initialize it with:

```bash
mkdir express-api-tutorial
cd express-api-tutorial
npm init -y
```

This generates a `package.json` file, which will track your project’s dependencies.

### **Step 2: Install Express.js**
Install Express as a dependency:

```bash
npm install express
```

### **Step 3: Create a Basic Express Server**
Create a file named `app.js` (or `server.js`) and add the following code:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const PORT = 3000;

// Define a simple route
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello, Express!');
});

// Start the server
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server is running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

### **Step 4: Run the Server**
Execute the server with:

```bash
node app.js
```

Visit `http://localhost:3000` in your browser or use **Postman** to send a `GET` request. You should see:

```
Hello, Express!
```

This confirms that Express is correctly installed and running.

---

## **Understanding Middleware in Express.js**

Middleware functions are the backbone of Express.js. They have access to the **request (req)**, **response (res)**, and the **next** middleware function in the cycle. Middleware can:
- Execute any code.
- Modify the request and response objects.
- End the request-response cycle (e.g., by sending a response).
- Call the next middleware function.

### **Types of Middleware**
1. **Application-level middleware** (applied using `app.use()` or `app.METHOD()`).
2. **Router-level middleware** (used in routers).
3. **Error-handling middleware** (handles errors).
4. **Third-party middleware** (e.g., `body-parser`, `cors`).

### **Example: Logging Middleware**
Let’s create a simple middleware that logs incoming requests:

```javascript
// Middleware to log requests
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log(`${req.method} ${req.url}`);
  next(); // Pass control to the next middleware
});
```

Add this before your route definitions. Now, every request (e.g., `GET /`) will log to the console:

```
GET /
```

### **Example: Parsing JSON Requests**
Express has built-in middleware to parse JSON payloads. To enable it:

```javascript
app.use(express.json()); // Parse JSON bodies
```

Now, if you send a `POST` request with a JSON body, Express will parse it into `req.body`:

```javascript
app.post('/api/users', (req, res) => {
  const { name, email } = req.body;
  res.json({ message: `User ${name} added!` });
});
```

Send a `POST` request with:
```json
{
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john@example.com"
}
```
The response will be:
```json
{
  "message": "User John Doe added!"
}
```

---

## **Routing in Express.js**

Routing refers to determining how an application responds to client requests for specific endpoints (URIs) and HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.).

### **Basic Routing**
Express provides methods to handle different HTTP verbs:
- `app.get()` for `GET` requests.
- `app.post()` for `POST` requests.
- `app.put()` for `PUT` requests.
- `app.delete()` for `DELETE` requests.

### **Example: Building a Simple API Endpoint**
Let’s create a RESTful endpoint for managing books. We’ll store books in memory (for simplicity) and define the following routes:

| Method | Endpoint       | Description                     |
|--------|----------------|---------------------------------|
| GET    | `/api/books`   | Get all books                   |
| POST   | `/api/books`   | Add a new book                  |
| GET    | `/api/books/:id` | Get a book by ID             |
| PUT    | `/api/books/:id` | Update a book by ID          |
| DELETE | `/api/books/:id` | Delete a book by ID          |

### **Step 1: Define In-Memory "Database"**
Add this at the top of `app.js`:

```javascript
let books = [
  { id: 1, title: "The Great Gatsby", author: "F. Scott Fitzgerald" },
  { id: 2, title: "1984", author: "George Orwell" }
];
let nextId = 3;
```

### **Step 2: Define Routes**
Add these routes below your middleware:

```javascript
// GET all books
app.get('/api/books', (req, res) => {
  res.json(books);
});

// POST a new book
app.post('/api/books', express.json(), (req, res) => {
  const { title, author } = req.body;
  if (!title || !author) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "Title and author are required" });
  }

  const newBook = { id: nextId++, title, author };
  books.push(newBook);
  res.status(201).json(newBook);
});

// GET a book by ID
app.get('/api/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const book = books.find(b => b.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (!book) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Book not found" });
  res.json(book);
});

// PUT (update) a book by ID
app.put('/api/books/:id', express.json(), (req, res) => {
  const book = books.find(b => b.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (!book) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Book not found" });

  const { title, author } = req.body;
  if (!title || !author) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "Title and author are required" });
  }

  book.title = title;
  book.author = author;
  res.json(book);
});

// DELETE a book by ID
app.delete('/api/books/:id', (req, res) => {
  const bookIndex = books.findIndex(b => b.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
  if (bookIndex === -1) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Book not found" });

  books.splice(bookIndex, 1);
  res.status(204).send(); // No content
});
```

### **Step 3: Test the API**
Use **Postman** or **curl** to test the endpoints:

1. **GET all books**:
   ```bash
   curl http://localhost:3000/api/books
   ```
   Response:
   ```json
   [
     { "id": 1, "title": "The Great Gatsby", "author": "F. Scott Fitzgerald" },
     { "id": 2, "title": "1984", "author": "George Orwell" }
   ]
   ```

2. **POST a new book**:
   ```bash
   curl -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"title":"The Hobbit","author":"J.R.R. Tolkien"}' http://localhost:3000/api/books
   ```
   Response:
   ```json
   { "id": 3, "title": "The Hobbit", "author": "J.R.R. Tolkien" }
   ```

3. **GET a book by ID**:
   ```bash
   curl http://localhost:3000/api/books/1
   ```
   Response:
   ```json
   { "id": 1, "title": "The Great Gatsby", "author": "F. Scott Fitzgerald" }
   ```

4. **PUT (update) a book**:
   ```bash
   curl -X PUT -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"title":"Animal Farm","author":"George Orwell"}' http://localhost:3000/api/books/2
   ```
   Response:
   ```json
   { "id": 2, "title": "Animal Farm", "author": "George Orwell" }
   ```

5. **DELETE a book**:
   ```bash
   curl -X DELETE http://localhost:3000/api/books/1
   ```
   Response: `204 No Content` (no response body).

---

## **Key Takeaways**
- **Express.js simplifies API development** by providing a structured way to handle routes, middleware, and requests/responses.
- **Middleware functions** are reusable and can

## Request Handling and Response Management

In the previous chapter, you learned how to set up a basic Express server and define routes. Now it's time to dive deeper into how Express processes incoming requests and how you can control the responses sent back to clients. This chapter will cover parsing request data, customizing HTTP responses, and implementing different response formats—essential skills for building robust APIs.

---

## Parsing Request Data

When a client sends a request to your API, it typically includes data in three main locations:
1. **Route parameters** (e.g., `/users/:id`)
2. **Query strings** (e.g., `/users?role=admin`)
3. **Request body** (e.g., JSON payload in POST/PUT requests)

Express provides built-in middleware to parse these data sources efficiently.

### 1. Accessing Route Parameters

Route parameters are defined directly in your route path and are accessed via the `req.params` object. For example:

```javascript
// Define a route with a parameter
app.get('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.params.id;
  // Fetch user with this ID from database
  res.json({ userId, status: 'success' });
});
```

When a client requests `/users/123`, `req.params.id` will be `"123"`. This is useful for retrieving specific resources (e.g., fetching a user by ID).

### 2. Parsing Query Strings

Query parameters are appended to the URL after a `?` and are accessed via `req.query`. Express automatically parses them into an object.

```javascript
// Example: /users?role=admin&sort=name
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  const { role, sort } = req.query;
  // Filter users by role and sort by field
  res.json({
    role,
    sort,
    message: 'Filtered users retrieved'
  });
});
```

Query strings are ideal for filtering, sorting, or paginating data.

### 3. Parsing Request Body

For POST, PUT, and PATCH requests that include a body (e.g., JSON or form data), you need middleware to parse it. Express has built-in support for JSON and URL-encoded data, but you must enable it:

```javascript
// Enable JSON body parsing
app.use(express.json());
// Enable URL-encoded body parsing (from form submissions)
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
```

Now you can access the parsed body via `req.body`:

```javascript
app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
  const { name, email } = req.body;
  // Create a new user with this data
  res.status(201).json({
    name,
    email,
    id: 1,
    message: 'User created'
  });
});
```

⚠️ **Important**: Always validate and sanitize incoming data. Never trust client input directly.

---

## Customizing HTTP Responses

HTTP responses consist of:
- A status code (e.g., 200 OK, 404 Not Found)
- Headers (e.g., `Content-Type`, `Cache-Control`)
- A body (e.g., JSON, HTML, plain text)

Express provides methods to control each of these components.

### 1. Setting HTTP Status Codes

Use `res.status(code)` to set the status code before sending the response:

```javascript
app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
  const { name, email } = req.body;
  if (!name || !email) {
    return res.status(400).json({
      error: 'Name and email are required'
    });
  }

  // If valid
  res.status(201).json({ id: 123, name, email });
});
```

Common status codes:
- `200 OK`: Successful GET request
- `201 Created`: Successful POST request (resource created)
- `400 Bad Request`: Invalid client input
- `401 Unauthorized`: Missing or invalid authentication
- `404 Not Found`: Resource doesn't exist
- `500 Internal Server Error`: Server-side error

### 2. Adding Headers

Headers provide metadata about the response. Use `res.set(header, value)` or `res.header()`:

```javascript
app.get('/secure-data', (req, res) => {
  res.set('Content-Type', 'application/json');
  res.set('Cache-Control', 'no-cache');
  res.json({ data: 'Sensitive information' });
});
```

Or chain it:

```javascript
res.status(200)
   .header('X-RateLimit-Limit', '100')
   .json({ message: 'API response' });
```

Common headers:
- `Content-Type`: Specifies the format of the response (e.g., `application/json`)
- `Authorization`: May include tokens for authenticated requests
- `ETag`: For caching and conditional requests
- `X-RateLimit-*`: Rate limiting information

---

## Implementing Response Formatting

APIs often need to return data in different formats depending on client needs or system design. Express makes it easy to send JSON, XML, or even plain text.

### 1. Sending JSON Responses

JSON is the most common format for REST APIs. Use `res.json(data)`:

```javascript
app.get('/api/data', (req, res) => {
  const data = {
    users: [
      { id: 1, name: 'Alice' },
      { id: 2, name: 'Bob' }
    ],
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString()
  };
  res.json(data);
});
```

This automatically sets the `Content-Type` to `application/json`.

### 2. Sending XML Responses

Some legacy systems or specific clients may require XML. While Express doesn't include XML parsing by default, you can use a library like `xml2js` to convert objects to XML:

```bash
npm install xml2js
```

```javascript
const { Builder } = require('xml2js');

app.get('/api/data.xml', (req, res) => {
  const data = {
    users: {
      user: [
        { id: 1, name: 'Alice' },
        { id: 2, name: 'Bob' }
      ]
    }
  };

  const builder = new Builder();
  const xml = builder.buildObject(data);

  res.type('application/xml');
  res.send(xml);
});
```

Example XML response:
```xml
<users>
  <user>
    <id>1</id>
    <name>Alice</name>
  </user>
  <user>
    <id>2</id>
    <name>Bob</name>
  </user>
</users>
```

### 3. Sending Plain Text or HTML

For simple responses or web pages:

```javascript
app.get('/about', (req, res) => {
  res.type('text/html');
  res.send('<h1>About Us</h1><p>We build APIs!</p>');
});

app.get('/status', (req, res) => {
  res.type('text/plain');
  res.send('Service is running');
});
```

---

## Real-World Example: Building a User API

Let’s build a simple user management API that uses all the concepts from this chapter.

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Middleware
app.use(express.json());
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

// In-memory "database"
let users = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
  { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' }
];

// GET /users - List all users (with query filtering)
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  const { role, sort } = req.query;
  let filteredUsers = users;

  if (role) {
    filteredUsers = filteredUsers.filter(user => user.role === role);
  }

  if (sort) {
    filteredUsers.sort((a, b) => a[sort].localeCompare(b[sort]));
  }

  res.status(200).json({
    count: filteredUsers.length,
    users: filteredUsers
  });
});

// GET /users/:id - Get a single user by ID
app.get('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const userId = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const user = users.find(u => u.id === userId);

  if (!user) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
  }

  res.json(user);
});

// POST /users - Create a new user
app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
  const { name, email, role = 'user' } = req.body;

  if (!name || !email) {
    return res.status(400).json({
      error: 'Name and email are required'
    });
  }

  const newUser = {
    id: users.length + 1,
    name,
    email,
    role
  };

  users.push(newUser);

  res.status(201)
     .header('Location', `/users/${newUser.id}`)
     .json(newUser);
});

